    <text>
        <body>
        	<div1 type="letter">
        		<pb entity="DSSR_000001107_0221"/>
        		<head>Jim to Mlle. Marcelle Guerin <date value="1916-01-13">Jan 13 1916</date></head>
        		
        		<opener>
            <dateline><date value="1916-01-13">January 13 1916</date></dateline>
            
            <salute>Dear Marcelle:</salute>
        		</opener>
        		
            <p>
            At last another
            free minute and I am
            using it to send you
            another line.  I have
            been passing along
            through the Pengouin
            or rolling classes and
            will be taking short
            jumps into the air
            in a week if the 
            weather permits.
            </p><p>
            Rumsey, the 
            American who had 
            such a bad fall
            
            <pb entity="DSSR_000001107_0223" n="[p.2]"/>
            
            made another try at it
            and broke his machine
            to bits over near the
            Spanish border.  Hard
            luck, but fortunate he
            was not hurt.  I don’t
            know what they’ll do
            to him.  It looks as
            if all the officers in
            the Army had congregated
            here for training.  Most 
            of them go to the
            Caudron.  I am going to
            try and take my brevet
            on a Bleriot for after
            learning that one can 
            run anything from a 
            pocket handkerchief to
            
            <pb entity="DSSR_000001107_0222" n="[p.3]"/>
            
            a sheet of blotting
            paper.
            </p><p>
            You ought to see
            me in my blue uniform.
            Feel stiff and foolish
            uncomfortable.  My khaki
            I’m keeping for state
            occasions as it looks
            better than the dress
            uniforms I’ve seen here 
            so far.  To morrow I’ll
            be given leathers and
            my troubles will be
            over.
            </p><p>
            Haven’t been to Pau
            as yet.  Last Sunday
            as I told you I passed
            at the little <unclear>run [sp?]</unclear> that
            
            <pb entity="DSSR_000001107_0224" n="[p.4]"/>
            
            is so quiet and comfortable.
            </p><p>
            I am going to try my
            best to be breveted as
            soon as possible, for
            after that I will have
            six days permission,
            and it will be 
            possible to see you
            again - and read Spoon 
            River and just be near
            you and happy.
            </p>
        		
        		<closer>
            <signed>Jim</signed>
        		</closer>
        		
            
